Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

Your code matches **two** patterns from the migration guide:

| API | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----|---------|-------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Timeout enforcement | `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException) { Thread.ResetAbort(); }` | ThreadAbortException as control flow | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |

## Why It Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime **cannot** forcibly terminate a managed thread. You must switch to cooperative cancellation where the work **voluntarily** checks a `CancellationToken`.

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token)
                       .GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## What Changed and Why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Func<T> work` | `Func<CancellationToken, T> work` | Work must receive a token to cooperate with cancellation |
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Tasks are the modern unit of async work; avoids manual thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` + `thread.Abort()` | `CancellationTokenSource(timeout)` | The CTS fires automatically after the timeout — no manual abort needed |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | `OperationCanceledException` is the cooperative equivalent |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | *(removed)* | No concept of "resetting" cooperative cancellation |
| *(nothing)* | `using var cts` | `CancellationTokenSource` is `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer leaks |

## Critical Pitfall: Callers Must Cooperate

The old `Thread.Abort` would forcibly interrupt **any** code. Cooperative cancellation only works if the `Func` actually checks the token. Callers must be updated:

```csharp
// ❌ OLD — ignores cancellation, will NOT stop at timeout
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct => ExpensiveCalculation(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ✅ NEW — checks the token at regular intervals
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in largeCollection)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

## Other Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Guidance |
|---------|----------|
| **Long gaps between checks** | If `Process(item)` takes 30s, cancellation won't fire until it finishes. Add checkpoints inside expensive operations too. |
| **Blocking I/O ignores the token** | `Thread.Sleep`, `socket.Receive`, etc. won't respond. Use `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or async I/O with token overloads. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures only timeout-caused cancellations become `TimeoutException`. External cancellations propagate correctly. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always `using` — it holds an internal timer that leaks otherwise. |
